<br>
<br>
The rule doesn't apply to single mobs, because no one stops mid-KT pull and runs off to whack Yelinak.  It just doesn't happen nor make sense.<br>
<br>
In VT, there really is no good place to stop, run out for rotation mobs, and then come right back to, and a little bit less so, N ToV (there is more than one safe spot for a COH mage, but they are spooky).  In VT,  you could stop after DXXT like you would on any first night of your VT clearing, and in N ToV, you usually would stop at Aary pit, even if you killed Vyemm or Fesh before stopping for the night.  In both cases, you get the protection of your mobs from other guilds running in and killing what you have left up.  Running out to kill other mobs, while holding those mobs &quot;hostage&quot; if you will, is hoarding.<br>
<br>
Another &quot;fear&quot;, especially with VT, is people might jump out to grab Cursed or Emp (the only mobs I can think of on rotation that might possibly be worth leaving VT for), and having a patch or server crash keep them from getting Aten, and then asking for an additional VT spot.  (Currently, if you clear day one, and there is a server down on day two before you get to Aten, you get another turn usually.)  So running out to whack Cursed, and then losing Aten, and insisting on a second full VT run is also quite a bit unfair.  You chose Cursed as being more important, and the server lost an Aten because of that choice.  This rule keeps that from happening.<br>
<br>
The rule didn't start when we passed mobs on our first VT, it started back in the N ToV days with SoT and BotS.  Before this rule, there was a lot of mob jumping when one guild would stop for the night, as people tried to grab whatever was left up.  The result, once SoT was fully on rotation (for a while, N ToV went dragon by dragon), this rule came into being, so that SoT (raided on euro time) and BotS (early EST) wouldn't have to worry about their mobs being taken over &quot;night&quot;.<br>
<br>
Since VT is much the same, the same rule applies.  NB has a mage logged out in several places in VT, so if this rule wasn't in place, we could easily wait till SOTE or FK stopped for the night, and run in and clear Named.  That wouldn't be very gentlemanly, and the rule makes sense.  However, much like the argument with teaming, it isn't very fair to the rest of the rotation guilds to grab a bunch of other mobs midraid while having those other mobs protected.<br>
<br>
It's really easy to deal with actually - if there is a mob up you really want (say Emp or Cursed), and it's before you start your VT run, you go grab them first, then head to VT.  If it's on the last day, finish VT and then go whack them.  If it spawns in the middle, and you take three days to clear VT, you probably won't be able to port out, kill the mob(s) and still clear VT in a timely manner anyway.  So this rule keeps mobs and multi-day rotations moving forward and keeps hoarding to a minimum.<br>
<br>
I completely agree that some guilds are capable of killing 8 mobs a night, and some take all night to kill 1, and both guilds should be protected under the system.  But let's remember one of the basics of the system - the faster mob X dies, the sooner he respawns for the next group.  Hoarding 6 named in VT while clearing 2-3 mobs outside is taking a tad bit advantage of the guild next up on rotation for VT who would gladly go in and clear those 6 Named (especially since one of those would be Aten).  It also risks that while hoarding those 6 VT Named, the server crashes as I pointed out above.  Basically, it comes down to priorities - which is more important, the named in VT or mob X, Y, or Z outside VT.  Make your choice if you won't have enough time to clear both, and pass the others.  If you can finish VT and the other mobs, more power to you.  The simple rule of thumb I use in choosing priorities: always choose your targets as if the server was going to crash imminently (which with SOE is always a possibility).<br>
<br>
So I would have to say that these factors lead me to continue to believe in and support the idea that if you leave a multi-day rotation spot, your rotation turn for those is done.  That way, the server is guaranteed, as much as is possible, that the best loot mobs will get killed as quickly as possible.  What I would say as a caveat, is that if you are able to kill a rotation mob with a small force, while STILL killing in VT or N ToV (think Trak or Statue), then I would have no problem with that.  Both rotations are moving forward, and you have not left VT or N ToV (in essence).  Obviously that applies to very few rotation mobs (i.e. you won't dispatch a Cursed or Emp force and still have numbers for VT).  The important deciding factor (for me) is, are you still actively killing in VT or N ToV? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#222222><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=karadin>Karadin</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NB-GM<BR>
And supermodel</span><br>  Posts: 466<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(5/22/03 1:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=342.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Some Curiosities about RTA Rules?</span><hr size=1> Lev,<br>
<br>
<br>
In your PoG example, Tunare is not a multi-day rotation.  And even were she, one could argue that you could have left 2-3 groups clearing, and sent 2-3 groups for Ragefire and been able to do both.  Especially in regards to the old Ragefire setup - which I would pass Tunare for to keep one of my clerics in line (assuming Ragefire wasn't one groupable).<br>
<br>
<br>
As for N ToV, any time a guild gets less than 2/3 of the spawn, and the zone crashes, they are within their &quot;rights&quot; to ask for another turn at N ToV.  The 2/3 number was created to keep guilds from leaving the triplets up (for lack of wanting their risk vs reward) and then claiming they &quot;lost&quot; mobs to a server down (which yes, happened).  However, Aaryonar isn't 2/3, and if that is all you got up to (Feshlak and Vyemm included), you would be well within your &quot;rights&quot; to ask for a second shot at N ToV if a server crash happened.<br>
<br>
Your specific CT example is a shade of grey to me.  You didn't stop N ToV to run out and go kill a mob and then rush back to N ToV.  You were done for the night, and those members left on, went to go take out a rotation mob.  You then went back in and finished your second day.  Having done N ToV and VT countless times, I know that no matter how much you might like people to camp in the room for a fast start the next day, someone (actually many someones) will want to go to the bazaar, xp, arena, whatever, so there is ALWAYS a need to COH for day 2.  What you did, as you point out, didn't take any time from N ToV than you already would have (you had finished for the night), and still kept CT rotation moving.  However, I would put CT closer to the side of Statue/Trak than I would Emp or Cursed in difficulty.<br>
<br>
What the rule is meant to do, is keep people from, mid-evening, TLing their whole force out of VT and running to kill Emp, Cursed, Tallon, etc (mobs that require significant numbers and are on rotation), and holding the VT mobs &quot;hostage&quot;.  If those other mobs are so important you would dump VT Named mid-raid to go grab, then you should let the next guild up have their shot at the VT named.  (N ToV could be substituted for VT in my above example).  You are risking a server crash eating Aten because these other mobs are so important. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#00FFFF>- </font><a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency>The Rathe Travel Agency Board</a><font color=#00FFFF> - </font><a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm11>Guild Representatives Forum</a> <font color=#00FFFF> - </font><a href="http://www.jakefitch.com/rta/Calendar.asp">The Rathe Calendar</a><font color=#00FFFF> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.245d<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

